---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import NavBar from "../components/NavBar.astro";
import Footer from "../components/Footer.astro";
---

<Layout
  title="About Us"
  description="About Board Foot Calculator — a modern free lumber calculator built for woodworkers, contractors, and DIYers. Fast, accurate, no fluff."
>
  <NavBar />

  <main class="bg-primary">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-8 py-16 sm:px-14 lg:px-24 lg:py-24">
      <span class="inline-block rounded-full bg-secondary px-3 py-1 text-caption-mono font-mono uppercase tracking-wide text-muted">
        About
      </span>
      <h1 class="mt-4 text-display-xl text-primary">About Board Foot Calculator</h1>

      <div class="mt-10 space-y-6 text-body-md text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        <p>
          I built this calculator because I got tired of the lumber math. Every time I started a new project — a desk, a set of shelves, a bench — I would end up with a scrap of paper covered in numbers, trying to figure out how many board feet I needed and whether I was getting a fair price at the yard. The online calculators I found were either too basic (single board, no pricing) or too complicated (sign-up required, buried in features I did not need).
        </p>
        <p>
          So I made my own. Something that works the way I actually think about a project: enter the boards I need, see the total volume and cost, adjust for waste, and move on. No accounts, no ads getting in the way, no fuss.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-display-sm text-primary mt-8">What it does differently</h2>
        <p>
          Most lumber calculators expect you to do one board at a time. Write down the number, clear the form, start over. This one lets you build a full cut list as you go. Add boards of different sizes, set quantities, and the running total updates automatically. Come back to it later — your list stays in the browser. The isometric preview is a nice bonus for catching mistakes: if the proportions look wrong, the numbers probably are too.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-display-sm text-primary mt-8">Who this is for</h2>
        <p>
          Woodworkers, contractors, DIYers — anyone who buys lumber by the board foot. If you price hardwoods for a living, you will appreciate the per-board cost breakdown. If you are building your first deck and just need to know how much pressure-treated pine to order, this works for that too. It handles both imperial and metric out of the box.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-display-sm text-primary mt-8">How it handles your data</h2>
        <p>
          The calculator runs entirely in your browser. Your cut list is saved to localStorage on your own machine. I never see it, I cannot access it, and there is no database involved. If you clear your browser data, the list goes with it. I use Google Fonts for the typography and AdSense for keeping the lights on, but no personal information is collected or shared.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-display-sm text-primary mt-8">Get in touch</h2>
        <p>
          Found a bug? Have a feature you would like to see? The best way to reach me is through the <a href="/contact" class="text-accent-mustard underline decoration-accent-mustard/30 hover:decoration-accent-mustard">Contact page</a>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </main>

  <Footer />
</Layout>
